// =============================================================================
// Math — the transcendental family. The BETA REDUCTION is documented on
// every method so the substitution chain is legible at source level.
// =============================================================================
//
// The whole philosophy of this language is that source beta-reduces, by
// substitution, down to substrate tensor/rotation operations. Every method
// here is `intrinsic` today — it routes to `_VSA.<name>` in
// codegen_pytorch.py — but the runtime body is NOT a libm call: it is the
// exact substitution written in each docstring, executed on the substrate
// as tensor ops. Read this file top to bottom and you can see every
// transcendental collapse onto two lookup-table leaves plus one
// eigenrotation.
//
// (Why intrinsic and not Sutra method bodies: the ideal form is
// `static method scalar pow(...) { return Math.exp(y * Math.log(x)); }`
// so the reduction is the source itself. The stdlib inliner does not yet
// resolve intra-`Math` member calls inside a class-bodied static method
// body — a NameError at codegen, surfaced honestly rather than papered
// over. Tracked as the top item of the substrate-leak audit. Until that
// inliner work lands, the reduction lives in the runtime + these
// docstrings; it is the same chain either way.)
//
// ── The two real lookup primitives ──────────────────────────────────────────
//
//   exp(a)   real exponential   — a codebook read by a crosstalk kernel
//   log(x)   natural logarithm  — the inverse codebook, same kernel
//
// "Lookup table" does NOT mean host array indexing. It is a rotational
// binding that uses the number: the input picks an angle, and the readout
// is a crosstalk-weighted sum over the codebook (triangular soft-index).
// The crosstalk between neighbouring entries is precisely what turns a
// discrete table into a *continuous* function. That weighting + dot is all
// tensor ops on the substrate — `_VSA._lerp` in codegen_pytorch.py.
//
// ── The eigenrotation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
//   cos(θ) = real part of the unit eigenrotation by θ
//   sin(θ) = imag part of the SAME rotation — cos with the signs flipped
//
// (cos θ, sin θ) together ARE the unit vector e^{iθ}. There is no separate
// "sine algorithm" — sine is the y-coordinate of the rotation whose
// x-coordinate is cosine.
//
// ── The keystone: the complex exponential ───────────────────────────────────
//
//   cexp(a, b) = exp(a) · (cos b + i·sin b)            [Euler's identity]
//
// The REAL factor exp(a) is the lookup leaf; the ROTATION factor
// (cos b + i·sin b) is the eigenrotation. Real exp BETA-REDUCES from it:
//
//   exp(x) ≡ real( cexp(x, 0) ) = real( exp(x)·(1 + 0i) ) = exp(x)
//
// `_VSA.exp` literally routes through `_VSA.cexp(x, 0)` on the substrate,
// so the beta reduction executes — it is not just a comment. Everything
// below is a one-line substitution onto exp / log / the eigenrotation.

class Math extends vector {

    // ── The substrate leaves ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //
    // exp  — real exponential. _VSA.exp routes through the complex
    //        exponential cexp(x,0): exp(x)·(cos 0 + i·sin 0) → exp(x).
    //        The real factor is the lookup codebook read by the crosstalk
    //        kernel; sin 0 = 0 collapses the imaginary part.
    // log  — natural log (JS Math.log = natural log, not base-10). The
    //        inverse codebook, same crosstalk kernel. Non-positive /
    //        out-of-range input saturates at the table edge (no raise —
    //        the no-runtime-errors rule).
    // cos  — real component of the unit eigenrotation by x.
    // sin  — imag component of the SAME rotation (cos, signs flipped).
    static intrinsic method scalar exp(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar log(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar cos(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar sin(scalar x);

    // ── Derived — runtime body is exactly the documented substitution ────────

    // ln — natural log; the conventional spelling used in the design
    //   notes. _VSA.ln is a direct alias of _VSA.log (`ln = log`): the
    //   substitution is the identity.
    static intrinsic method scalar ln(scalar x);

    // pow — change-of-base identity:  x^y = exp(y · ln x).
    //   _VSA.pow body: self.exp(self._st(y) * self.log(x)) — one log
    //   leaf, one tensor multiply, one exp leaf. x > 0 (log domain);
    //   x ≤ 0 saturates at the log table edge, not a raise.
    static intrinsic method scalar pow(scalar x, scalar y);

    // sqrt — the y = 1/2 case of pow:  √x = exp(0.5 · ln x).
    //   _VSA.sqrt body: self.exp(0.5 * self.log(x)). x near 0 saturates
    //   at the log table edge — an honest reflection of the codebook.
    static intrinsic method scalar sqrt(scalar x);

    // tan — the rotation's slope:  sin / cos, the imag/real ratio of
    //   the eigenrotation. At odd multiples of π/2 cos → 0 and the
    //   quotient tensor → ±inf (the mathematically-valid limit; no host
    //   `if cos == 0`, consistent with JS Math.tan).
    static intrinsic method scalar tan(scalar x);

    // ── Hyperbolics — pure exp combinations, no new substrate ────────────────
    //
    // sinh = (e^x − e^−x)/2   cosh = (e^x + e^−x)/2
    // tanh = (e^{2x} − 1)/(e^{2x} + 1)   [numerically-stable form]
    // _VSA bodies are exactly these, on exp leaves + tensor arithmetic;
    // for large |x| exp saturates at the table edge so tanh → ±1, the
    // correct limit reached without a host range check.
    static intrinsic method scalar sinh(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar cosh(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar tanh(scalar x);
		
		//I have no clue how it is that you repeatedly got this so wrong. I don't know how it is you repeatedly got this so wrong, but I'm actually manually writing the exponential function in because of the fact that it's fucking obvious to me and the fact that you aren't understanding it is really really disappointing. There's no such thing as a scalar in this, and I'm pretty sure that the entire class of a scalar, as you use it, is basically just a substrate leak. I'm pretty sure that this entire thing is just a substrate leak, even though it's fucking easy. 
		public static number exp(number x){
		//this is the actual style of comment I want
		//no bloaty to the point of unreadable
		//as per rules of exponentiation x^(a*b) = x^a * x^b
		return realExp(x.real) * imaginaryExp(x.imaginary);
}

